    <text>
        <body>
            <head>11. Memorandum From the President’s Assistant for National Security Affairs
                    (<persName corresp="rec5nWAotd8wedNxI">Clark</persName>) to President <persName
                    corresp="rec5PPNCl6qqfgBAq">Reagan</persName><note n="1" place="foot"
                    type="source" xml:id="d11fn1">Source: National Security Council, <orgName
                        corresp="recft7WGb7Fww0wma">National Security Council</orgName>
                    Institutional Files, Box SR—101, <gloss target="#t_NSC_1"><orgName
                            corresp="recft7WGb7Fww0wma">NSC</orgName></gloss> 00049, <gloss
                        target="#t_RWR_1">RWR</gloss> 5/03/82 <gloss target="#t_START_1"><rs
                            corresp="recGzN4S83GSdMO7O" type="event">START</rs></gloss>. Top Secret.
                    Prepared by <persName corresp="rec1MI7pNjlwnDZyR">Kraemer</persName> and
                        <persName corresp="rec3WaAgwEDeqcFLV">Linhard</persName>. An unknown hand
                    wrote in the upper right-hand corner: “PRESIDENT HAS SEEN.”</note>
            </head>
            <opener>
                <dateline rendition="#right">
                    <placeName>Washington</placeName>, <date calendar="gregorian" when="1982-05-02"
                        >May 2, 1982</date>
                </dateline>
            </opener>
            <list type="subject">
                <head>SUBJECT</head>
                <item>
                    <gloss target="#t_NSC_1"><orgName corresp="recft7WGb7Fww0wma"
                        >NSC</orgName></gloss> Meeting, Monday, May 3, 1982</item>
            </list>
            <p>
                <hi rendition="simple_italic">Issue:</hi> What should be the basic elements of the
                US negotiating position on <gloss target="#t_START_1"><rs
                        corresp="recGzN4S83GSdMO7O" type="event">START</rs></gloss>?</p>
            <p>
                <hi rendition="simple_italic">FACTS/DISCUSSION:</hi> The <gloss target="#t_IG_1"
                    >IG</gloss> has prepared a paper (Tab D)<note n="2" place="foot" xml:id="d11fn2"
                    >Not attached.</note> forwarding agency views on: 1) the units to be limited; 2)
                Interim Restraints to be applied or sought during the negotiations; and 3) Other
                Issues.</p>
            <p>The issues of Interim Restraints and Other Issues will need to be addressed in the
                weeks ahead before we begin negotiations. No decisions on these can or should be
                made prior to deciding the unit of account issue. The main issue and focus of
                today’s meeting will be on what the basic units to be limited by a <gloss
                    target="#t_START_1"><rs corresp="recGzN4S83GSdMO7O" type="event"
                    >START</rs></gloss> agreement should be. Decisions will be incorporated in a
                draft <gloss target="#t_NSDD_1">NSDD</gloss>.</p>
            <p>All agencies are agreed that the <gloss target="#t_START_1"><rs
                        corresp="recGzN4S83GSdMO7O" type="event">START</rs></gloss> units of
                limitation should be radically different from the <rs corresp="reckP3QiieAZd7kwE"
                    type="topic">launcher</rs> focus of <gloss target="#t_SALT_1"><rs
                        corresp="rec6OIA4luUvtBKNn" type="event">SALT</rs></gloss>. All are agreed
                that there should be a ceiling of 5,000 warheads (about a 1/3 cut from today’s US
                levels) with possible further reductions down the road. All are agreed that <rs
                    corresp="rectLhSs11Y4ZQ6zE" type="topic">bombers</rs> should be treated
                differently from <rs corresp="recr08QgEMEm1Bk04" type="topic">missiles</rs>, and
                that there should be an eventual ceiling of some 250 <rs corresp="rectLhSs11Y4ZQ6zE"
                    type="topic">bombers</rs> on each side. All are agreed that there must be limits
                on <rs corresp="reclksm3VX3UUxetF" type="topic">throwweight</rs> as a vital
                component of <rs corresp="recZ01lWtQiA1vZuI" type="topic">military capability</rs>
                and as the category which most clearly gives the <placeName
                    corresp="rec7g4kEoiXWBjoX3">Soviet Union</placeName> strategic advantages. There
                is disagreement on how <rs corresp="reclksm3VX3UUxetF" type="topic">throwweight</rs>
                should be limited, with some favoring <pb facs="0068" n="39" xml:id="pg_39"/> direct
                limits (e.g., an overall ceiling), and others favoring indirect limits, as on <gloss
                    target="#t_ICBM_1"><rs corresp="reccap2GMokKh4v4P" type="topic"
                    >ICBMs</rs></gloss>, warhead weight, etc. There is also disagreement on how the
                individual agency proposals meet your <rs corresp="recQ5xJqddmHqhjNl" type="topic"
                    >arms control</rs> criteria.</p>
            <p>At Tab A is a chart<note n="3" place="foot" xml:id="d11fn3">Attached but not printed
                    is an undated chart entitled “Agency Views on <gloss target="#t_START_1"><rs
                            corresp="recGzN4S83GSdMO7O" type="event">START</rs></gloss> Negotiation
                    Position.”</note> summarizing the various agency approaches on the unit of
                limitations issues. At Tab B is a chart<note n="4" place="foot" xml:id="d11fn4"
                    >Attached but not printed is an undated chart.</note> comparing the agency
                positions in terms of their impact on the <rs corresp="reclksm3VX3UUxetF"
                    type="topic">throwweight</rs> limitations question.</p>
            <p>A final issue, is what should be said in your May 9 speech about the US position and
                the initiation of <gloss target="#t_START_1"><rs corresp="recGzN4S83GSdMO7O"
                        type="event">START</rs></gloss>. The draft insert at Tab C,<note n="5"
                    place="foot" xml:id="d11fn5">Attached but not printed is an undated draft paper
                    entitled “President’s May 9 speech—<gloss target="#t_START_1"><rs
                            corresp="recGzN4S83GSdMO7O" type="event">START</rs></gloss>
                    Insert.”</note> prepared by the <gloss target="#t_START_1"><rs
                        corresp="recGzN4S83GSdMO7O" type="event">START</rs></gloss>
                <gloss target="#t_IG_1">IG</gloss>, appears to offer an appropriate approach.</p>
        </body>
    </text>
